06361nam a22009735i 9789048535125DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a9789048535125  a(DE-B1597)577355  a(OCoLC)1259320423  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBL410b.T65 2021eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a201.522300aTolerance, Intolerance, and Recognition in Early Christianity and Early Judaism /ced. by Michael Labahn, Outi Lehtipuu. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (314 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Christianity in the Roman World ;v200tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tContributors -- tI Conditions of Tolerance -- t1. From Conflict to Recognition -- t2. Mutable Ethnicity in the Dead Sea Scrolls -- t3. Der geliebte „Feind“ -- tII Jewish–Christian Relations between Tolerance and Intolerance -- t4. Was Paul Tolerant? -- t5. Since When Were Martyrs Jewish? -- t6. Hiding One’s Tolerance -- t7. Rabbinic Reflections on Divine– Human Interactions -- tIII Tolerance and Questions of Persecution, Gender, and Ecology -- t8. Were the Early Christians Really Persecuted? -- t9. “No Male and Female” -- t10. Learning from “Others” -- tEpilogue -- tIndex of Ancient Sources0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays investigates signs of toleration, recognition, respect and other positive forms of interaction between and within religious groups of late antiquity. At the same time, it acknowledges that examples of tolerance are significantly fewer in ancient sources than examples of intolerance and are often limited to insiders, while outsiders often met with contempt, or even outright violence. The essays take both perspectives seriously by analysing the complexity pertaining to these encounters. Religious concerns, ethnicity, gender and other social factors central to identity formation were often intertwined and they yielded different ways of drawing the limits of tolerance and intolerance. This book enhances our understanding of the formative centuries of Jewish and Christian religious traditions. It also brings the results of historical inquiry into dialogue with present-day questions of religious tolerance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aJudaismxHistoryyTalmudic period, 10-425. 0aReligionsxRelationsxHistory. 0aReligious tolerancexHistory. 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aearly Judaism, early Christianity, tolerance, intolerance, religious recognition.1 aDowling, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunderberg, Ismo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarjanmaa, Sami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabahn, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabahn, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLehtipuu, Outi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehtipuu, Outi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevine, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiddleton, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikki, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRafael, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc